1. What is DevOps?
- DevOps is a set of practices, tools, and a cultural mindset that integrates software development (Dev) and IT operations (Ops) to enhance collaboration, automate workflows, and improve the efficiency of software delivery.
The main goal of DevOps is to shorten the software development lifecycle and ensure continuous integration, continuous delivery (CI/CD), and high software reliability through automation and monitoring.

Key Concepts in DevOps
🔹 CI/CD (Continuous Integration & Continuous Deployment) – Automating code building, testing, and deployment.
🔹 Infrastructure as Code (IaC) – Managing infrastructure using code (e.g., Terraform, Ansible).
🔹 Configuration Management – Automating server and software setup (e.g., Chef, Puppet).
🔹 Monitoring & Logging – Ensuring system health (e.g., Prometheus, Grafana, ELK Stack).
🔹 Cloud Computing – Deploying on cloud platforms (AWS, Azure, GCP).
🔹 Containerization & Orchestration – Using Docker & Kubernetes for scalable applications.

